Here's a complete example. I'll create the project structure with a tool class wrapping a REST API and a properly configured `Program.cs`.

---

### **Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`**

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Fetches a user profile by ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync($"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Creates a new user with the given name and email.")]
    public async Task<string> CreateUser(
        [Description("Display name for the user")] string name,
        [Description("Email address")] string email,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Creating user {Name}", name);
        var payload = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new { name, email });
        var content = new StringContent(payload, System.Text.Encoding.UTF8, "application/json");

        var response = await httpClient.PostAsync("/users", content, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool(ReadOnly = true), Description("Lists all users, optionally filtered by role.")]
    public async Task<string> ListUsers(
        [Description("Filter by role (e.g. 'admin', 'member'). Leave empty for all.")] string? role = null,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var url = string.IsNullOrEmpty(role) ? "/users" : $"/users?role={role}";
        return await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

---

### **`Program.cs` — stdio transport**

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: stdio uses stdout for JSON-RPC — all logs must go to stderr
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
    client.DefaultRequestHeaders.Add("Accept", "application/json");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### **How DI works for MCP tools**

The SDK supports **two injection styles**, and the key insight is that DI-resolved parameters **never appear in the tool's JSON schema** — the LLM only sees parameters with `[Description]`.

| Style | How it works |
|-------|-------------|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | The class gets a DI-registered service via its constructor. The SDK creates an instance per invocation, resolving all constructor params from the DI container. This is the pattern above — `HttpClient` and `ILogger<T>` are injected via the primary constructor. |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services appear directly as method parameters. The SDK checks each param's type — if it's registered in DI, it injects it; otherwise it exposes it in the schema. |

**Auto-injected types** (no registration needed):

- `CancellationToken` — cooperative cancellation
- `IMcpServer` — access to the server instance
- `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>` — report progress to the client

**You register everything else** in `Program.cs`:

```
AddHttpClient<T>()    → typed HttpClient
AddSingleton/Scoped() → your own services
ILogger<T>            → built-in, no registration needed
```

The SDK discovers tool classes via `.WithToolsFromAssembly()` (reflection scan) or `.WithTools<ApiTools>()` (explicit, AOT-safe).
